{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4900e58f-377c-453b-943a-4ebfce101e9f","content":"I've reviewed all the files. Here are the **3 evaluation performance anti-patterns** in this project:\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (line 13, `EvalHeavy.csproj`)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files via `System.IO.File` during evaluation is expensive — it blocks the evaluation pipeline with disk I/O on every build invocation, even no-op builds.\n\n### 2. Overly Broad Glob (line 9, `EvalHeavy.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the **entire directory tree**, matching every file. This is costly in repos with deep or large directories (e.g., `node_modules`, `.git`). The exclude list only filters `bin/obj` — everything else is enumerated.\n\n**Fix:** Narrow the glob to specific extensions you actually need, or add large directories to `DefaultItemExcludes` early in evaluation.\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import adds evaluation overhead (file existence checks, parsing, property/item merging). At 3 levels this is modest, but it's a pattern that compounds — chains >20 levels deep become a measurable bottleneck. Use `dotnet msbuild -pp:full.xml EvalHeavy.csproj` to visualize the full flattened import graph.\n\n### Summary\n\n| Issue | Severity | Location |\n|---|---|---|\n| `File::ReadAllText` in property | **High** | Line 13 |\n| `**\\*.*` glob | **High** | Line 9 |\n| 3-level import chain | **Low** | Line 6 → imports/ |\n\nThe file I/O and broad glob are the most impactful. Move file reads to a target (execution phase) and tighten the glob pattern to specific file types.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a93a6195-1a58-44ab-b03d-a08323434339","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the evaluation performance issues:\n\n1. **Deep import chain**: `EvalHeavy.csproj` → `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props` (3 levels deep). While this is only 3 levels, it's still a pattern that can grow.\n\n2. **Expensive glob pattern**: `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />` - This is a very broad glob that walks the entire directory tree, matching every file with an extension.\n\n\n3. **File I/O during evaluation**: There's a property function that reads from disk at build time, which adds unnecessary I/O overhead. Let me check the eval-performance skill for guidance on optimizing these patterns.","outputTokens":737},"id":"8fff539d-d693-4bc5-8746-58be1963ec9d","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:11:34.985Z","parentId":"4771c77a-93d7-48a0-bc3a-744f15e031d5"}
